VI'd like to introduce you to an emerging area of science,
p4
aVone that is still speculative but hugely exciting,
p5
aVand certainly one that's growing very rapidly.
p6
aVQuantum biology asks a very simple question:
p7
aVDoes quantum mechanics \u2014
p8
aVthat weird and wonderful and powerful theory
p9
aVof the subatomic world of atoms and molecules
p10
aVthat underpins so much of modern physics and chemistry \u2014
p11
aValso play a role inside the living cell?
p12
aVIn other words: Are there processes, mechanisms, phenomena
p13
aVin living organisms that can only be explained
p14
aVwith a helping hand from quantum mechanics?
p15
aVNow, quantum biology isn't new;
p16
aVit's been around since the early 1930s.
p17
aVBut it's only in the last decade or so that careful experiments \u2014
p18
aVin biochemistry labs, using spectroscopy \u2014
p19
aVhave shown very clear, firm evidence that there are certain specific mechanisms
p20
aVthat require quantum mechanics to explain them.
p21
aa(lp22
VQuantum biology brings together quantum physicists, biochemists,
p23
aVmolecular biologists \u2014 it's a very interdisciplinary field.
p24
aVI come from quantum physics, so I'm a nuclear physicist.
p25
aa(lp26
VI've spent more than three decades
p27
aVtrying to get my head around quantum mechanics.
p28
aVOne of the founders of quantum mechanics, Niels Bohr,
p29
aVsaid, If you're not astonished by it, then you haven't understood it.
p30
aVSo I sort of feel happy that I'm still astonished by it.
p31
aVThat's a good thing.
p32
aVBut it means I study the very smallest structures in the universe \u2014
p33
aVthe building blocks of reality.
p34
aVIf we think about the scale of size,
p35
aVstart with an everyday object like the tennis ball,
p36
aVand just go down orders of magnitude in size \u2014
p37
aVfrom the eye of a needle down to a cell, down to a bacterium, down to an enzyme \u2014
p38
aVyou eventually reach the nano-world.
p39
aa(lp40
VNow, nanotechnology may be a term you've heard of.
p41
aVA nanometer is a billionth of a meter.
p42
aVMy area is the atomic nucleus, which is the tiny dot inside an atom.
p43
aVIt's even smaller in scale.
p44
aVThis is the domain of quantum mechanics,
p45
aVand physicists and chemists have had a long time
p46
aVto try and get used to it.
