VI want to share with you just a few of the exciting ones.
p156
aVThis is one of the best-known phenomena in the quantum world,
p157
aVquantum tunneling.
p158
aVThe box on the left shows the wavelike, spread-out distribution
p159
aVof a quantum entity \u2014 a particle, like an electron,
p160
aVwhich is not a little ball bouncing off a wall.
p161
aVIt's a wave that has a certain probability of being able to permeate
p162
aVthrough a solid wall, like a phantom leaping through to the other side.
p163
aVYou can see a faint smudge of light in the right-hand box.
p164
aVQuantum tunneling suggests that a particle can hit an impenetrable barrier,
p165
aVand yet somehow, as though by magic,
p166
aVdisappear from one side and reappear on the other.
p167
aVThe nicest way of explaining it is if you want to throw a ball over a wall,
p168
aVyou have to give it enough energy to get over the top of the wall.
p169
aVIn the quantum world, you don't have to throw it over the wall,
p170
aVyou can throw it at the wall, and there's a certain non-zero probability
p171
aVthat it'll disappear on your side, and reappear on the other.
