aa(lp247
VAnother example of quantum mechanics in biology is quantum coherence,
p248
aVin one of the most important processes in biology,
p249
aVphotosynthesis: plants and bacteria taking sunlight,
p250
aVand using that energy to create biomass.
p251
aVQuantum coherence is the idea of quantum entities multitasking.
p252
aVIt's the quantum skier.
p253
aVIt's an object that behaves like a wave,
p254
aVso that it doesn't just move in one direction or the other,
p255
aVbut can follow multiple pathways at the same time.
p256
aa(lp257
VSome years ago, the world of science was shocked
p258
aVwhen a paper was published showing experimental evidence
p259
aVthat quantum coherence takes place inside bacteria,
p260
aVcarrying out photosynthesis.
p261
aVThe idea is that the photon, the particle of light, the sunlight,
p262
aVthe quantum of light captured by a chlorophyll molecule,
p263
aVis then delivered to what's called the reaction center,
p264
aVwhere it can be turned into chemical energy.
